{
  "doc_id": "1113",
  "text": "Initiation of minus strand RNA synthesis occurs after the bottom portion of the 3′ SL stem and the 3′ sHP stem have opened followed by long distance pairing of 3′ and 5′ sequences (Fig. 3) . As discussed in Section 3, a conserved metastable region in the 3′ SL is involved in regulating the opening of the lower part of the stem [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] ) but the region of the 3′ NCR to which these proteins bound was not mapped and some of these proteins also bound to additional flavivirus RNA terminal sequences (De Nova-Ocampo, [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] as well as to some of the viral proteins [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Additional studies identified cell proteins binding to particular regions within the flavivirus 3′ NCR. La, MOV34, YB-1, P100(NF-κB2), PTB, and eEF1a [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] were reported to bind to a flavivirus 3′ SL, DDX6 was reported to bind to 5′ DB and 3′ DB [CITATION_19] and Caprin 1, G3BP1/2 and USP10 were reported to bind to the VR of the 3′ NCR [CITATION_20] .",
